metadata.name: On the sea, I ... #177
metadata.description:
Generative painting based on churning waves with floating buoys. Represented in three different media.

Features:
- Three drawing styles: "watercolor" 70%, "brush" 30%, or "block" 70%
- Warm white or blue waves
- Variable border and column sizes
- Number of columns
- Calm waves at the edges or center
- Color 80% or red 20% buoys
- Buoy drawing style, "watercolor" or "brush"

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 928x1200px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a variation of your edition at a resolution up to 3,000 px.

metadata.name: Rondelle, Listen #186
metadata.description:
Tap to start sound. Tap to mute.

Inspired by the glass rondelles which hung from the windowsill in my childhood home. I ask myself what would these rondelles sound like if they reflected sound instead of light? To me, I hear hopeful harmonies of memories past, but they are falling in and out of tune and they are occluded by the muffled noise of time.

When a rondelle is minted, a transaction hash is injected into its code. All colors, patterns, sounds, and motions are generated deterministically from this transaction hash.

As the rondelle loads in your browser, a real-time generative algorithm writes tones, noise, feedback, and distortion to three looping audio buffers. During playback, oscillations in pan, pitch, and volume track the visual oscillations among the rondelle's color rings.

Rarity features are included. The least common rondelles are closed center, monochrome, smol, split color, and square.

Made with Web Audio and p5js. Minted on fxhash beta. Idlebit, 2021.

metadata.name: Organicon, variation III - final form #105
metadata.description:
Generative art by Frederik Vanhoutte, @wblut
one of 1024 unique generators creating an endless sequence of iterations with fixed features

Organicon, variation III - final form, is a celebration of exuberance and abundance, a closing piece meant to build slowly on the screen. A small counter in the lower-right corner displays the progress.

Interface: on first load the piece operates in active mode. In this mode an iteration is cleared 30s after completion and replaced by the next iteration. This mode is indicated by a flashing dot in the upper-right corner.

A first mouse click disables active mode. The current iteration will complete and remain on screen. A second mouse click clears the screen, loads the next iteration, and reenables active mode.

metadata.name: The Abstract Truth III #259
metadata.description:
Moiré patterns meet halftone dots meet cross stitching.

Halftone is a term that can refer to both a technology used in image processing and as the synonym for semitone in music. A jazz musician Oliver Nelson released the album The Blues and the Abstract Truth in 1961. It is considered one of the most significant records of its time. In addition, he wrote Patterns for Improvisation, a hugely popular jazz patterns book. The Moiré pattern design is on the book's cover.

Look out for the FOMO keyboard key to unlock more variations. 
Press 'P' to pause/unpause the animation.

metadata.name: WTBS: Wearable #1 (cap edition) #16
metadata.description:
The Waiting is over. It’s actually happening. We’ve teased, hinted, and honestly YEARNED for this release. We hope you enjoy.

WTBS: Wearable #1 (cap edition) is a celebration of the 3rd anniversary of the Waiting To Be Signed Podcast. We mark this milestone in collaboration with artist Anna Lucia and are extremely pleased to bring you these one-of-a-kind generative caps. Each NFT in this series is an animated digital artwork which contains the embroidery design for a unique cap. When you obtain an NFT from this collection, you’re not only collecting digital art, you can also redeem a cap featuring the very design! 

Get your cap: 

Anna Lucia has curated a full collection using fx(hash)’s params function. At the time of sale, all NFTs will have already been minted by Anna Lucia & ready for sale. You can acquire your preferred design by placing an offer of $75 or more (in TEZ equivalent), which will be accepted by Anna. This price includes the NFT & cap but excludes shipping. Cap redemption will be handled via Artfora.com. 
If you are not buying the cap directly from Anna Lucia’s wallet (tz1M7dt8sWC64ZXkmiWbttVCtgFrFU6Do9x9), please view the collection on Artfora to check whether the cap has already been redeemed or not. 

Controls:

The NFT itself showcases the dynamic, animated generative design. Use the interactive controls to explore variations and preview how your chosen design will look on the embroidered cap. There are two colors cap, black and desert beige, represented by the background color and reflected in the mock-up. 

A -> Toggle between animated view and cap mock-up
D -> Download the embroidery file 
E -> Detailed view of embroidery design 
R -> Record and download a .zip file of 300 frames

On mobile only the digital animated view is available. 

This work is created with p5.js and stitch.js.

metadata.name: ‘Low-Res’ poems #47
metadata.description:
‘Low-Res’ poems is a collection as a high-tech alternative search. It was made with two free small, lightweight softwares like kidpix.app and magicavoxel, using the @PureSpider template to create iterations. This collection  is produced from technological limitations, a socioeconomic condition implies a determined political position and this is reflected on the access to technology, mainly the access to hardware.
As an artist, not having access to specialized high-tech hardware and software made my workflow, or the way I approach art, different, putting me in a place where I had to open myself and embrace low-poly or low-res alternatives to continue making art.

‘Low-Res’ has 50 MagicaVoxel models in 3D and 6 backgrounds made in kidpix.app, in each piece, the features combinations build corny poems, which give each piece an unique spirit and name. These poems work as a continuation of the Digital Collage collection.

High res tech has often been a vector of cultural hegemony over the global south, especially in terms of access to the tech- Sabatobox @sabatobox
